blocks.name: cdioph
blocks.content: Extend class notation to include the family of Diophantine sets.

blocks.name: df-dioph
blocks.content: A Diophantine set is a set of positive integers which is a projection of the zero set of some polynomial. This definition somewhat awkwardly mixes ` ZZ ` (via ` mzPoly ` ) and ` NN0 ` (to define the zero sets); the former could be avoided by considering coincidence sets of ` NN0 ` polynomials at the cost of requiring two, and the second is driven by consistency with our mu-recursive functions and the requirements of the Davis-Putnam-Robinson-Matiyasevich proof. Both are avoidable at a complexity cost. In particular, it is a consequence of ~ 4sq that implicitly restricting variables to ` NN0 ` adds no expressive power over allowing them to range over ` ZZ ` . While this definition stipulates a specific index set for the polynomials, there is actually flexibility here, see ~ eldioph2b . (Contributed by Stefan O'Rear, 5-Oct-2014.)
blocks.origin:
axiom df-dioph(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3, setvar s4) {
  |- wceq(cdioph, cmpt(s0, cn0, crn(cmpo(s1, s2, cfv(cuz, cv(s0)), cfv(cmzp, co(nat1, cfz, cv(s1))), cab(s3, wrex(s4, co(cn0, cmap, co(nat1, cfz, cv(s1))), wa(wceq(cv(s3), cres(cv(s4), co(nat1, cfz, cv(s0)))), wceq(cfv(cv(s2), cv(s4)), nat0))))))))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s1, s2)
  -| diffss(s1, s3)
  -| diffss(s1, s4)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
  -| diffss(s0, s3)
  -| diffss(s0, s4)
  -| diffss(s2, s3)
  -| diffss(s2, s4)
  -| diffss(s3, s4)
}
blocks.pretty:
axiom df-dioph(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3, setvar s4) {
  ⊢ Dioph =(s0 ∈ ℕ0 ↦ ran((s1 ∈(ℤ≥ ` s0), s2 ∈(mzPoly `(1[...]s1))↦ { s3 | ∃(s4 ∈(ℕ0[↦](1[...]s1)),(s3 =(s4 |`(1[...]s0))∧(s2 ` s4)= 0))})))
  ⊣ d(s0, s1)
  ⊣ d(s1, s2)
  ⊣ d(s1, s3)
  ⊣ d(s1, s4)
  ⊣ d(s0, s2)
  ⊣ d(s0, s3)
  ⊣ d(s0, s4)
  ⊣ d(s2, s3)
  ⊣ d(s2, s4)
  ⊣ d(s3, s4)
}

blocks.name: eldiophb
blocks.content: Initial expression of Diophantine property of a set. (Contributed by Stefan O'Rear, 5-Oct-2014.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 22-Sep-2015.)

blocks.name: eldioph2
blocks.content: Construct a Diophantine set from a polynomial with witness variables drawn from any set whatsoever, via ~ mzpcompact2 . (Contributed by Stefan O'Rear, 8-Oct-2014.) (Revised by Stefan O'Rear, 5-Jun-2015.)

  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
  -| diffsc(s0, c1)

  -| diffsc(s1, c0)
  -| diffsc(s1, c1)

} = {
  mpd(w3a(wcel(c0, cn0), wa(wcel(c1, universe), wss(co(nat1, cfz, c0), c1)), wcel(c2, cfv(cmzp, c1))), wcel(cab(s0, wrex(s1, co(cn0, cmap, c1), wa(wceq(cv(s0), cres(cv(s1), co(nat1, cfz, c0))), wceq(cfv(c2, cv(s1)), nat0)))), cfv(cdioph, c0)), wrex(hs0, cfn, wrex(hs2, cfv(cmzp, cv(hs0)), wa(wss(cv(hs0), c1), wceq(c2, cmpt(hs1, co(cz, cmap, c1), cfv(cv(hs2), cres(cv(hs1), cv(hs0)))))))))

blocks.name: eldioph2b
blocks.content: While Diophantine sets were defined to have a finite number of witness variables consequtively following the observable variables, this is not necessary; they can equivalently be taken to use any witness set ` ( S \ ( 1 ... N ) ) ` . For instance, in ~ diophin we use this to take the two input sets to have disjoint witness sets. (Contributed by Stefan O'Rear, 8-Oct-2014.)

thm eldioph3b(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, class c0, class c1) {

  -| diffsc(s2, c0)
  -| diffsc(s2, c1)
} = {
  a1ii(wb(wcel(c0, cfv(cdioph, c1)), wa(wcel(c1, cn0), wrex(s0, cfv(cmzp, cn), wceq(c0, cab(s1, wrex(s2, co(cn0, cmap, cn), wa(wceq(cv(s1), cres(cv(s2), co(nat1, cfz, c1))), wceq(cfv(cv(s0), cv(s2)), nat0)))))))), diffsc(s1, c0))
  a1ii(wb(wcel(c0, cfv(cdioph, c1)), wa(wcel(c1, cn0), wrex(s0, cfv(cmzp, cn), wceq(c0, cab(s1, wrex(s2, co(cn0, cmap, cn), wa(wceq(cv(s1), cres(cv(s2), co(nat1, cfz, c1))), wceq(cfv(cv(s0), cv(s2)), nat0)))))))), diffsc(s2, c0))

  eldiophelnn0(c0, c1)
  mpan2(wcel(c1, cn0), wb(wcel(c0, cfv(cdioph, c1)), wrex(s0, cfv(cmzp, cn), wceq(c0, cab(s1, wrex(s2, co(cn0, cmap, cn), wa(wceq(cv(s1), cres(cv(s2), co(nat1, cfz, c1))), wceq(cfv(cv(s0), cv(s2)), nat0))))))), wcel(cn, universe))

thm eldioph3(setvar s0, setvar s1, class c0, class c1) {

  -| diffsc(s0, c1)
  -| diffsc(s1, c0)
